Here is the breakdown of the head command, which is typically the next step when you want to look inside the files you've been creating and moving:

head
The head command is used to view the beginning (the "head") of a text file directly inside the terminal. By default, it prints the first 10 lines of the specified file.

Bash
head notes.txt
⚙️ Modifying the Output with Flags
If you don't want exactly 10 lines, you can control how much text is shown using options:

-n <number> (Specify Lines): Tells the command exactly how many lines from the top you want to read.

Bash
head -n 5 log.txt
(This will display only the first 5 lines of log.txt).

Short-hand Syntax: You can omit the -n flag entirely and just pass a hyphen followed by the number:

Bash
head -5 log.txt